","Stimulates pancreatic enzyme secretion"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe primary action of secretin is to \u003Cstrong\u003Estimulate pancreatic bicarbonate secretion\u003C/strong\u003E. When acidic chyme enters the duodenum, S cells release secretin, which then acts on the pancreas to increase bicarbonate output. This helps neutralise stomach acid in the duodenum and creates an optimal pH for pancreatic enzyme function.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreases gastric acid production\u003C/strong\u003E - Secretin inhibits gastric acid secretion\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStimulates cholecystokinin release\u003C/strong\u003E - Secretin and cholecystokinin are independent hormones with different stimuli\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreases gastric emptying\u003C/strong\u003E - Secretin slows gastric emptying\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStimulates pancreatic enzyme secretion\u003C/strong\u003E - Pancreatic enzyme secretion is primarily stimulated by cholecystokinin, not secretin\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESecretin\u0027s actions help maintain duodenal pH and coordinate the digestive process by slowing gastric emptying until adequate bicarbonate is available to neutralise acid.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Secretin is released from S cells in the duodenum in response to acidic chyme.","The primary action of secretin is to stimulate bicarbonate secretion from the pancreas.","Secretin also decreases gastric acid secretion and gastric emptying."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019","Asbury, C., Rieke, F., Hille, B., Bothwell, M., \u0026 Tuthill, J. (2023) Physiology. Simple Book Publishing. https://uw.pressbooks.pub/physiology/."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55058"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17229"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55058","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/55058"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-12T11:18:13+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-12T11:18:47+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9919"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69606"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4928","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4928"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udca9","name":"Gastrointestinal","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:16: